<SubSubSection title="Rolling on a flat surface" id="rolling_flat_surface" >

    <p>
        The most common and also the simplest form of rolling occurs
        on a flat surface.
      </p>
      <PrairieDrawCanvas width="600" height="600" id="rko-ff-c">
        <p class="controls">
          <button class="anim-toggle:rko-ff-c" onclick="rko_ff_c.toggleAnim()">animation</button>
          <button class="reset:rko-ff-c" onclick="rko_ff_c.reset()">reset</button>
        </p>
        <p class="controls">
          <button class="option-toggle:rko-ff-c:showPaths"onclick="rko_ff_c.toggleOption('showPaths')">show paths</button>
          <button class="option-toggle:rko-ff-c:reversed" onclick="rko_ff_c.toggleOption('reversed')">reverse direction</button>
        </p>
        <p class="figureCaption">
          Geometry and variables for rolling without slipping on a
          flat surface.
        </p>
      </PrairieDrawCanvas>
      <p>
        While rolling, the velocity and acceleration are directly
        connected to the angular velocity and angular acceleration,
        as shown by the next equations.
      </p>
    <DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{aligned}            \\vec{v}_C &amp;= r \\omega \\,\\hat{e}_t \\\\            \\vec{a}_C &amp;= r \\alpha \\,\\hat{e}_t            \\end{aligned}" background="True" title="Center velocity and acceleration while rolling on a flat surface (Tangential-Normal Basis)." id="rko-ef" derivation="True">
        <p>
            We begin by observing that the sign conventions in
            Figure <a href="#rko-ff">#rko-ff</a> mean that
            <InlineEquation equation="\\vec\\omega = -\\omega\\,\\hat{e}_b" />. Now rolling without
            slipping means the contact point \(A\) must
            instantaneously have zero velocity, so using <a
            href="rkg.html#rkg-er">#rkg-er</a> gives:

            <DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{aligned}            \\vec{v}_C &amp;= \\vec{v}_A + \\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{r}_{AC} \\\\            &amp;= (-\\omega \\,\\hat{e}_b) \\times r \\,\\hat{e}_n \\\\            &amp;= r \\omega \\,\\hat{e}_t.            \\end{aligned}" />

            Because the surface is flat, the tangential basis vector
            <InlineEquation equation="\\hat{e}_t" /> is constant, and the radius \(r\) is also
            constant. Differentiating the velocity expression thus
            results in:

            <DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{aligned}            \\vec{v}_C &amp;= r \\omega \\,\\hat{e}_t \\\\            \\dot{\\vec{v}}_C &amp;= r \\dot\\omega \\,\\hat{e}_t \\\\            \\vec{a}_C &amp;= r \\alpha \\,\\hat{e}_t.            \\end{aligned}"/>
          </p>
    </DisplayEquation>


    <DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{aligned}            \\vec{v}_C &amp;= -r \\omega_z \\,\\hat\\imath \\\\            \\vec{a}_C &amp;= -r \\alpha_z \\,\\hat\\imath            \\end{aligned}" background="True" id="rko-ef2" title="Center velocity and acceleration while rolling on a flat surface (Standard Basis)." derivation="True">
        <p>
            Since the body is rolling without slipping, the contact point \(A\)'s
            velocity is instantaneously zero. Using rigid body equations:

            <DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{aligned}            \\vec{v}_C &amp;= \\vec{v}_A + \\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{r}_{AC} \\\\            &amp;= \\omega_z r_{AC}^\\perp \\\\            &amp;= -r \\omega_z \\,\\hat\\imath.            \\end{aligned}"/>

            Differentiating to obtain acceleration results in:

            <DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{aligned}            \\vec{v}_C &amp;= -r \\omega_z \\,\\hat\\imath \\\\            \\dot{\\vec{v}}_C &amp;= -r \\dot\\omega_z \\,\\hat\\imath \\\\            \\vec{a}_C &amp;= -r \\alpha_z \\,\\hat\\imath.            \\end{aligned}"/>
          </p>
    </DisplayEquation>

      <p>
        Another way to express the connection between angular and
        linear velocity and acceleration is via the distance \(s\)
        traveled by the rolling body:
      </p>

    <DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{aligned}            s &amp;= r \\theta \\\\            \\dot{s} &amp;= r \\omega \\\\            \\ddot{s} &amp;= r \\alpha            \\end{aligned}" background="True" id="rko-eh" title="Distance-angular relationships for rolling on a flat surface." derivation="True">
        <p>
            The contact point \(P\) and center \(C\) are offset by the
            constant vector <InlineEquation equation="r\\,\\hat{e}_n" /> so <InlineEquation equation="\\dot{s} = v_P = v_C            = r\\omega" />, from <a href="#rko-ef">#rko-ef</a>. Because
            \(r\) is constant, differentiating the velocity expression
            gives <InlineEquation equation="\\ddot{s} = r \\dot\\omega = r \\alpha" />, while
            integrating with zero initial displacement gives <InlineEquation equation=" s = r            \\theta" />.
          </p>
    </DisplayEquation>
      <p>
        While rolling, the contact point will have zero velocity but
        will have a centripetal acceleration towards the rolling
        center:
      </p>

        <DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{aligned}            \\vec{v}_P &amp;= 0 \\\\            \\vec{a}_P &amp;= \\omega^2 \\,\\vec{r}_{PC}            \\end{aligned}" background="True" title="Contact point \\(P\\) velocity and acceleration while rolling on a flat surface." id="rko-eo" derivation="True">
            <p>
                By definition of non-slip rolling contact, the point of
                contact \(P\) has zero velocity. The acceleration can be
                computed from the center \(C\) with <a
                href="#rkg-e2">#rkg-e2</a>:
    
                <DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{aligned}            \\vec{a}_P &amp;= \\vec{a}_C + \\vec{\\alpha} \\times \\vec{r}_{CP}            + \\vec{\\omega} \\times (\\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{r}_{CP}) \\\\            &amp;= \\alpha r \\,\\hat{e}_t + (-\\alpha\\,\\hat{e}_b) \\times (-r\\,\\hat{e}_n)            + (-\\omega\\,\\hat{e}_b) \\times \\Big((-\\omega\\,\\hat{e}_b) \\times (-r\\,\\hat{e}_n)\\Big) \\\\            &amp;= \\alpha r \\,\\hat{e}_t - \\alpha r \\,\\hat{e}_t            + \\omega^2 r \\,\\hat{e}_n \\\\            &amp;= \\omega^2 \\,\\vec{r}_{PC}.            \\end{aligned}"/>
              </p>
        </DisplayEquation>

</SubSubSection>


<SubSubSection title="Rolling on curved surfaces"  id="rolling_curved_surface">
    <p>
        When a circular rigid body rolls without slipping on a
        surface which is itself curved, the radius of curvature of
        the surface affects the acceleration (but not velocity) of
        points on the rolling body.
    </p>

    <PrairieDrawCanvas id="rko-fc-c" width="600" height="600"></PrairieDrawCanvas>

    <DisplayEquation id="rko-eg" derivation='True' background="True" title="Geometric quantities for rolling on a curved surface." equation="\\begin{aligned} \\left.\\begin{aligned} R &amp;= \\rho - r \\\\ \\vec{\\omega} &amp;= -\\omega \\,\\hat{e}_b \\\\ \\vec{\\alpha} &amp;= -\\alpha \\,\\hat{e}_b \\end{aligned}\\right\\} &amp; \\text{ when rolling on the inside of a curved surface} \\\\[1em] \\left.\\begin{aligned} R &amp;= \\rho + r \\\\ \\vec{\\omega} &amp;= \\omega \\,\\hat{e}_b \\\\ \\vec{\\alpha} &amp;= \\alpha \\,\\hat{e}_b \\end{aligned}\\right\\} &amp; \\text{ when rolling on the outside of a curved surface} \\end{aligned}"> 
            These formulas are all choices of sign conventions for
            <InlineEquation equation="\\omega" /> and <InlineEquation equation="\\alpha" />, and definitions of <InlineEquation equation="R" />. Figure <a
            href="#rko-fc">#rko-fc</a> shows the appropriate
            geometry. Note that <InlineEquation equation="\\omega" /> and <InlineEquation equation="\\alpha" /> are defined
            with positive values corresponding to motion in the
            tangential direction.
    </DisplayEquation>

    <!-- WARNING -->
    <p>Warning: Radii of curvature <InlineEquation equation="\\rho" /> and
    <InlineEquation equation="R" /> may not be constant.</p>
    <p>
        The radius of curvature <InlineEquation equation="\\rho" /> of the surface may be
        varying with position as the body rolls. If <InlineEquation equation="\\rho" />
        changes then this will also cause <InlineEquation equation="R" /> to change. These
        two variables will only be constant if the surface is in
        fact perfectly circular.
      </p>
</SubSubSection>


